SAKHILE NDLAZI The community of Mamelodi have come out in numbers to pay their last respects to little Katlego Katli Joja. Tears flowed as a little white coffin was ushered in to the church. Various civic groups, political parties and government officials also came to pay their tribute. The Deputy Minister of Police, Bongani Mkongi said because of Katli people are now more wiser about autism and he understood it too well. “Autism, is not a disease but a condition. My nephew was born with autism,“ he said. To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web browser that
    supports HTML5 video This is a modal window. Beginning of dialog window. Escape will cancel and close the window. End of dialog window.  He also assured the community that the police did handle the case with urgency. It is alleged that the police delayed in assisting the family to search for the girl who was living with autism and was unable to speak. The family said they were turned back several times by the police and were told to wait for 24-hours before they could open a missing person’s case. Her body was found floating in the Moretele river on Sunday afternoon after she had been missing for four days. Her principal Karen Dick said they will have a Katlego Joja Bursary and Katlego Joja Search and Rescue in Mamelodi. The police have opened an inquest docket said Police spokesperson Captain Johannes Maheso.